{{Infobox military conflict| image=| caption=| conflict=Battle of the Trent| partof=| date=c.679| place= at or near the [[River Trent]] (in modern-day [[England]])| coordinates=| result= Mercian victory| |combatant1=[[Mercia]] |combatant2=[[Northumbria]]| commander1=[[Æthelred of Mercia|Æthelred]]| commander2=[[Ecgfrith of Northumbria|Ecgfrith]]| strength1=| strength2=| casualties1=| casualties2=| }} {{Campaignbox Anglo-Saxon invasions}} The '''Battle of the Trent''' was a battle fought at an unspecified site near the [[River Trent]] within the [[Kingdom of Lindsey]] (today part of [[England]]), in 679. The battle was fought between the [[Northumbria]]n army of King [[Ecgfrith of Northumbria|Ecgfrith]] and the [[Mercia]]n army of King [[Æthelred of Mercia|Æthelred]].<ref name=Kirby_93>Kirby, ''Earliest English Kings'', p.&nbsp;93.</ref><ref name=Bede_IV_21>Bede, ''Ecclesiastical History'', IV, 21, p.&nbsp;240.</ref> The Mercians were victorious, ending Northumbrian domination of the area. Lindsey remained part of Mercia until the Viking invasion of the 9th century.
Bede notes that the 18-year-old subking, [[Ælfwine of Deira]], was killed in the battle, and that this almost led to further conflict between the two kingdoms, needing the intervention of [[Theodore of Tarsus|Theodore]], the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]].<ref>Bede, ''[[Historia ecclesiastica gentis Anglorum|Historia ecclesiastica]]'', [http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/basis/bede-book4.html Book IV, chapter 21].</ref>
In his account of the battle, [[Bede]] recounts the tale of a Northumbrian [[thegn]] called Imm or Imma, who may have been the founder of the settlement of [[Immingham]]. Imma was captured by the Mercians and, proving troublesome, was sold into slavery to a [[Frisia]]n merchant who, when his identity was discovered, then ransomed him to one of the [[King of Kent|kings of Kent]].<ref name="Bede_IV_21"/>
